{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MDjFGiukibmRGhVp5Cwa8U","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three nodes are back in the cluster. Here's what was wrong and how it was fixed:\n\n**Root cause:** The `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` Secret had `rabbitmq-2` set to a different Erlang cookie (`driftedcookie`) than the other two nodes (`supersecretcookie`). Erlang nodes refuse to communicate with nodes that have mismatched cookies, so `rabbitmq-2` initialized its own standalone Mnesia database instead of joining the existing cluster.\n\n**Fix (three steps):**\n1. **Patch the Secret** — set `rabbitmq-2`'s entry in `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` to the correct `supersecretcookie` value (base64: `c3VwZXJzZWNyZXRjb29raWU=`).\n2. **Delete the pod** — the init container (`copy-cookie`) only runs at pod start, so `rabbitmq-2` needed a restart to pick up the corrected cookie from the Secret.\n3. **Reset and rejoin** — because `rabbitmq-2` already had Mnesia data from its standalone startup (on the PVC), peer discovery wouldn't re-run automatically. Manually ran `rabbitmqctl stop_app && rabbitmqctl reset && rabbitmqctl join_cluster rabbit@rabbitmq-0... && rabbitmqctl start_app` to wipe the stale local metadata and rejoin the cluster.\n\nThe cluster now shows all 3 nodes in both Disk Nodes and Running Nodes with no alarms and no network partitions."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":976,"cache_read_input_tokens":40513,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":976},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e25624df-e95f-44d1-a1ff-2e7ab7d85c5b","uuid":"572216bc-8841-424b-90f3-bcacfb40bb6d","request_id":"req_011CcLBA6w92wYcrUc9TjUmd"}
